          questionType: 'passage',
          questionSubType: 'retrieval',
          passageId: 'hedgehog-life',
          passageTitle: "The Secret Life of Hedgehogs",
          passage: "As dusk falls over a quiet suburban garden in Hampshire, a small, prickly creature emerges from beneath a pile of fallen leaves. The hedgehog, one of Britain's most beloved mammals, is beginning its nightly search for food. With around five thousand spines covering its back, this little animal may look fierce, but it is actually one of the gentlest creatures you could hope to meet.\n\nHedgehogs are nocturnal, which means they are active mainly at night. During the daytime, they sleep in nests called hibernacula, which they build from leaves, grass and twigs. These nests are surprisingly well-constructed — a hedgehog will spend several days gathering materials and weaving them together to create a warm, waterproof shelter. A single hedgehog may have several nests dotted around its territory, moving between them throughout the warmer months.\n\nOne of the most remarkable things about hedgehogs is their ability to hibernate. As autumn temperatures drop below freezing, hedgehogs curl into a tight ball inside their nest and enter a deep sleep that can last from November right through to March. During hibernation, their heart rate drops from around 190 beats per minute to just 20, and their body temperature falls dramatically. They survive entirely on fat reserves built up during the summer and autumn, when they feast on slugs, beetles, caterpillars and earthworms.\n\nSadly, hedgehog numbers in Britain have declined sharply over the past twenty years. Scientists estimate that the population has fallen from approximately thirty million in the 1950s to fewer than one million today. The main threats include loss of hedgerows, busy roads, pesticides that kill their insect prey, and garden hazards such as uncovered drains and netting. Conservation groups across the country are working hard to reverse this decline. Simple actions like leaving a gap at the bottom of garden fences, creating log piles for shelter, and avoiding slug pellets can make an enormous difference to these charming animals.\n\nIf you are lucky enough to spot a hedgehog in your garden, the best thing you can do is leave out a shallow dish of fresh water and some cat biscuits. Never give them bread or milk, as this can make them very ill. With a little care and attention, we can all help to protect these wonderful creatures for generations to come.",
